https://prez.dev/description.@value: The point or level from which heights and depths are measured and referenced to for an entity or activity. Typically these are expressed relative to a common global or regional reference datum such as the Australian Height Datum (AHD) or can be related to local reference systems. Specific emphasis is placed on elevation references used by resource exploration and drilling programs, whereby depths are measured relative to local reference datums or specific parts of a borehole/drilling platform. Concepts in this vocabulary include both reference datums (e.g. mean sea level) and how depths are expressed relative to them (e.g. mean sea level height).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: The 'Australian Height Datum (Tasmania) 1983' (AHD–TAS83) zero reference is fixed to mean sea level (MSL) observed for 1972 only at tides gauges in Hobart and Burnie, and was propagated throughout Tasmania on 17 October 1983. Because AHD (mainland) and AHD (Tas) are referenced to MSL observed at different times and locations, there is a vertical offset between the two datums (variably estimated at about 10 cm, between 12 cm and 26 cm, and about 1 cm (https://www.icsm.gov.au/australian-height-datum). Note that the term AHD is used to refer to both the Australian Height Datum 1971 (AHD71; Australian mainland) and Australian Height Datum (Tasmania) 1983 (AHD–TAS83).
